psychiatrist said he did not think gould would carry out the 
threats 
mirin a past president of the massachusetts psychiatric 
society is associate director of mclean hospital in belmont a 
teaching hospital of harvard medical school 
his attorney charles reidy argued that the jury was swayed by 
prejudice and passion not reason and that the verdict was wrong 
as a matter of law 
paul sugarman attorney for the rotmans contended that the 
psychiatrist was negligent because he failed to adequately warn the 
victim notify police or restrain gould 
mirin had written rotman a letter telling her that gould had 
talked of harming her but sugarman argued that the letter should 
have been stronger and more explicit and that mirin should have 
hospitalized gould 
when you get someone this sick you owe a duty to protect 
people sugarman said you owe a duty to see that hes removed 
from the community or at least from the ability to do harm 
after the killing gould was found innocent of murder by reason 
of insanity and was placed at bridgewater state hospital the 
hospital declined to say tuesday whether he is still a patient 
there 
