<TEXT>
a continental airlines report filed with federal 
safety inspectors blames the fatal november crash of a dc9 at 
stapleton international airport on wing turbulence a poorly plowed 
runway and airtraffic control errors 
flight 1713 crashed upon takeoff during a snowstorm killing 28 
people 
a combination of errors by the city of denver and airtraffic 
control caused the catastrophic crash of flight 1713 the airline 
concluded in the report filed last month with the national 
transportation safety board the rocky mountain news reported in 
todays edition 
the evidence developed to date indicates the crash of flight 
1713 was not caused by mechanical or equipment failure structural 
icing or pilot error the report said rather the crash was 
caused by the aircraft encountering wingtip vortices at a critical 
phase of flight 
a wingtip vortex is turbulence resulting from an intense eddy 
of swirling air that fans out from the wings of airplanes 
particularly widebody planes 
in response to continentals claim that the city did not 
completely clear the runway stapleton spokesman richard boulware 
said we reject that categorically i personally sat in my office 
that day and watched airplanes take off from that very runway 
nobody else had any problem why did they and if continental did 
the pilot had the option of choosing not to take off 
frank johns airtraffic manager at stapleton said he hadnt 
seen the report so i dont have any specific comments but we 
would probably disagree with those findings 
continental spokesman bruce hicks said the ntsb has barred the 
airline from releasing the 54page report filed july 11 and a 
50page aug 5 supplemental document that further argues turbulence 
from another airplane caused the crash 
ntsb spokesman ted lopatkiewicz said the board will not comment 
on the investigation until sept 27 when it is expected to 
announce its findings in the nov 15 crash 
an air line pilots association report filed with the ntsb 
alleges inadequate aircraft deicing and incomplete crew training 
by continental caused the crash the report also said the copilot 
lee edward bruecher mishandled the jets controls contributing to 
the severity of the crash 
the 26yearold copilot and pilot frank zvonek 43 were among 
those killed 
in its report continental contends turbulence from the wings of 
a delta boeing 767 that landed on a runway parallel to the one used 
by flight 1713 less than three minutes before takeoff was the 
primary cause of the accident 
continental also contends the pilots injuries and damage to 
cockpit controls indicate zvonek recognized the severity of the 
votexinduced loss of control at a critical phase of the flight 
and assumed control of the aircraft 
in addition to turbulence and runway conditions the continental 
report cited airtraffic controllers for allegedly 
failing to report clutter or slush on the runway and to 
request an inspection of the runway 
failing to provide proper spacing between landings and 
departures on the parallel runway to avoid turbulence 
failing to properly chart flight 1713s position prior to 
departure causing a delay of up to seven minutes in takeoff which 
may have affected airplane deicing 
failing to report wind direction and velocity accurately 
