<TEXT>
north korea today said it would meet 
with south korean delegates friday to prepare for a joint 
parliamentary session on a nonaggression pact and the norths 
demand to cohost the olympics 
south koreas national assembly said north koreas supreme 
peoples assembly agreed in a telephone message to send five 
delegates to the truce village of panmunjom on friday it would be 
the first time in nearly three years that the two koreas have met 
facetoface 
both sides last met in december 1985 at red cross talks at 
panmunjom but the north shelved all interkorea dialogue in early 
1986 to protest regular joint military exercises between south 
korea and the united states 
the latest peace overtures began july 21 when the north 
proposed that a joint session of the parliaments draft a 
nonaggression pact it later proposed that they discuss the 
olympics which open sept 17 in seoul 
north korea has said it will boycott the olympics unless it is 
allowed to cohost them south korea and international olympic 
officials have rejected the demand because the games are awarded 
only to one city 
north korea had proposed the meeting for today but the south 
suggested moving it to friday so it wouldnt interfere with 
celebrations marking 30 days before the olympics begin 
an assembly source speaking on condition of anonymity said the 
norths message today did not mention its earlier demand for 
fullfledged parliamentary talks the two sides have disagreed over 
the norths demand to include representatives of all walks of life 
in the main legislative conference 
the north also insists fridays meeting should discuss only 
logistical arrangements for main talks but the south wants to take 
up all basic and procedural matters including the agenda and the 
size of full negotiations 
the disagreement cast doubts on the prospects of full 
parliamentary talks between the two koreas which were divided in 
1945 at the end of world war ii and which fought the korean war 
from 1950 to 1953 
some south korean government officials said north korea may have 
agreed to the preliminary talks in an attempt to stir unrest before 
the olympics or to find an excuse to boycott the olympics 
but south koreas opposition parties welcomed the norths 
agreement 
we hope the southnorth parliamentary talks would provide an 
opportunity for realizing national unification said a message 
from the main opposition party for peace and democracy 
the proposed parliamentary talks could involve nearly 600 
lawmakers from communist north korea and capitalist south korea 
the norths offiical korean central news agency in a report 
monitored in tokyo said the norths delegation to fridays talks 
would be headed by chon gum chol representative of the communist 
workers party and the supreme peoples assembly 
south koreas national assembly has named park joonkyu a 
senior member of the governing democratic justice party to head 
its fivemember delegation which also includes members of the 
three main opposition parties and one other member of the governing 
party 
on tuesday north korea rejected the international olympic 
committees latest compromise proposal that the two koreas march 
sidebyside at the opening and closing ceremonies 
north korea sees the awarding of the games to seoul and a 
successful staging of the olympiad as a major victory for its 
rival it also has argued that letting seoul alone host the games 
will bring world recognition of a divided korean peninsula and 
further delay reunification 
</TEXT>
