<TEXT>
a strike by coal miners demanding the 
legalization of the outlawed solidarity trade union spread 
wednesday with employees at a second mine and dock workers in 
szczecin joining the labor unrest 
about 3000 miners have been holed up in the july manifesto 
complex near jastrzebie for two days early wednesday workers at 
the morcinek coal mine near the czech border put down their tools 
to support them 
workers at the july manifesto mine declared an occupation strike 
tuesday and demanded the reinstatement of solidarity crushed by 
the communist government in 1981 they also want pay raises and the 
rehiring of workers fired for independent trade union activities 
on wednesday 600 workers occupied the szczecin docks after a 
failed round of talks with management and another 400 might join 
in said jan kostecki a solidarity leader in the port of szczecin 
about 250 miles northwest of warsaw 
a prosecutor immediately declared the strike illegal solidarity 
officials said adding that a strike committee was formed 
officials at the port in szczecin which employs 7000 people 
and is polands secondlargest after gdansk confirmed only that 
strike efforts were under way at the port 
the mines are about 12 miles apart in silesia polands most 
industrialized region about 280 miles southwest of warsaw 
we support all of the demands of the july manifesto mine 
workers said andrzej andrzejczak head of morcineks strike 
committee 
he said workers raised a large polish flag atop the main 
administration building and that young miners wearing red and white 
armbands blocked the entrance to the mine 
solidarity strike committee members at july manifesto said they 
would strike until their demands are met 
solidarity strike committee members met with mine management and 
industry ministry representatives at july manifesto adam 
kowalczyk a regional solidarity leader had no details of the 
talks which continued late wednesday 
officials at both mines were unavailable for comment 
a strike committee communique earlier wednesday said mine 
management refused to allow food into the mine and the committee 
appealed to community residents to bring bread to the front gate 
people could be seen throwing bread over the walls that surround 
the facility bread was not delivered to stores in nearby apartment 
complexes wednesday 
police closed off access to the mine tuesday after about 4000 
workers refused to pick up their tools about 3000 workers are 
still in the yard inside the complex witnesses said 
public transportation remained suspended wednesday 
it was not immediately known how many miners were striking at 
morcinek the mine built in 1986 employs about 2300 workers 
about 9000 workers are employed at the july manifesto mine one 
of polands largest and a key producer of highgrade export coal 
miners leaving the july manifesto facility early wednesday said 
the wage demands were based on hardships caused by polands 
worsening economy and its 60 percent inflation 
the economy is in ruins one miner told the associated 
press miners cannot live on their salaries because of recent 
price hikes 
polands miners are paid nearly twice the national average and 
receive extra benefits because of the vital role they play in the 
nations economy 
poland is the worlds fourth largest exporter of coal and its 
mining operations are also essential to the nations steel power 
and shipbuilding industries 
the government has declared the strike illegal strikers at july 
manifesto on tuesday defied an order to end the occupation 
the staterun news agency pap in a dispatch wednesday called 
the strikes political provocation and said the workers demands 
are getting more and more radical 
july manifesto was a hotbed of labor activism during a wave of 
strikes that spawned solidarity eight years ago 
in 1980 the government signed an agreement with miners at the 
manifesto facility recognizing solidarity after a series of strikes 
crippled mining operations in silesia 
poland had five strikes from april 25 to may 10 and brief work 
stoppages or strike threats in 25 more workplaces in the worst 
labor unrest in the country since the 1981 martiallaw crackdown 
the workers in those strikes also demanded the legalization of 
solidarity and wage increases 
