<TEXT>
the tiny black homeland of 
venda in south africas northeast corner is in turmoil because of 
ritual murders and allegations that officials have tried to cover 
them up 
thousands of students have boycotted classes for two weeks 
demanding the justice minister be fired and workers joined the 
protest tuesday with a general strike that continues affecting 
government offices public transport shops and factories 
president frank ravele said after an emergency cabinet meeting 
tuesday that alfred tshivhase had been dismissed as justice 
minister to restore law and order but would be kept on as 
minister without portfolio 
police in venda confirm four ritual murders have been committed 
this year and are being investigated but have not disclosed 
details they deny charges of a coverup made by student and 
community leaders who claim the true number of killings is 15 
ritual murder is a term used in africa to describe killings in 
which parts of bodies are cut off ground up and used as an 
ingredient in potions children are the most frequent victims 
the south african foreign ministry said tuesday there had been 
false rumors of a coup in venda reports of political turbulence in 
the homeland have circulated since patrick mphephu the 
authoritarian president died in april after nearly 30 years in 
power 
venda is twothirds the size of lebanon and its population is 
about 500000 many of them migrant workers whose jobs are far from 
the territory it is one of four black homelands designated as 
independent by south africa but not recognized abroad 
a coup attempt failed earlier this year in bophuthatswana one 
of the homelands and a coup succeeded last year in another 
transkei 
venda was declared independent in 1979 and human rights groups 
have described its government as ruthless in suppressing political 
dissent 
the sowetan south africas largest blackoriented daily 
newsdpaper reported wednesday that suspects in two of the four 
confirmed ritual murder cases were connected with the government 
it said a member of the legislature was accused of killing an 
18yearold woman but freed when the attorney general declined to 
prosecute and a man working for the director of intelligence 
services had been arrested in the murder of a baby 
no official information has been released about motives for the 
murders 
the sowetan said many students involved in the classroom boycott 
have been arrested and fellow protesters were demanding their 
release 
another south african newspaper the star said wednesday that 
students submitted a statement to police alleging that tshivhase 
the justice minister was linked to the death last month of a 
32yearold high school teacher 
