<TEXT>
by selecting indiana sen dan quayle as his 
running mate george bush has reached out to a region whose voters 
have more clout than anyone else 
thanks to the nations changing population it will take fewer 
midwestern votes to win delegates to the electoral college than in 
any other region of the nation 
electoral college support is hardest to come by on the other 
hand in the south home to democratic vice presidential nominee 
lloyd bentsen and also claimed by the gops bush 
this is the case because despite the oneperson onevote 
theory americans dont elect their presidents directly instead 
they elect delegates to the electoral college who in turn actually 
pick the president and vice president 
and the number of delegates each state gets in the electoral 
college is based on the total number of senators and 
representatives that state has in congress every state has two 
senators while seats in the house are readjusted according to 
population after each national census 
that means that for this election representation in the 
electoral college is based on the 1980 national head count even 
though massive changes have occurred as people moved from state to 
state 
the south has the most electoral votes at 177 this year 
followed by 137 in the midwest 113 in the west and 111 in the 
northeast the census bureau estimates that as of july 1 1987 
the south had 63032000 residents aged 18 and over second was the 
midwest at 43952000 the northeast with 38402000 and the west 
at 37242000 
that means each electoral vote in the midwest represents 320817 
voters the fewest of any region and thus giving them the most 
clout as individuals when they do to the polls 
the western voter comes next in influence with each elector 
representing 335513 voters each elector from the northeast 
represents 339841 voters while in the south the ratio is 356112 
voters per electoral vote 
thus each voter in the midwest has 11 percent more influence on 
the election than someone going to the polls in the south 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

