<TEXT>
the united states today detonated a 
nuclear device under this remote desert mesa in a historic test 
monitored by soviet scientists under an agreement allowing both 
countries to observe nuclear weapons tests 
scientists diplomats and military officials applauded in the 
control center after the nuclear device exploded at 10 am 
causing a ripple on the desert surface at ground zero the blast 
was not felt at the center 30 miles away where it was observed on 
television screens 
it was the first time soviet officials had been allowed to 
monitor a weapons test at the supersecret nevada test site 
the nuclear explosive with a blast nearly 12 times more 
powerful than the one that devastated hiroshima was buried 2020 
feet into the belly of a secluded picturesque mesa 130 miles 
northwest of las vegas 
the weapon was encased in a steel canister painted red white 
and blue by workers who planted the device three weeks ago 
in las vegas people in tall buildings reported the blast caused 
some swaying 
everything appears successful so far said nick aquilina 
manager of the nevada operations office which conducts the 
nations nuclear testing program the us and soviet scientists 
received the data they wanted he said 
in santa barbara calif white house spokesman marlin 
fitzwater with president reagan on vacation called todays test 
a further positive step which reflects the success of the 
administrations practical and measured approach to nuclear 
testing 
diplomats who helped forge the agreement in geneva late last 
year gathered at the control point joining scientists and military 
officials who direct the nuclear weapons programs for the two 
superpowers 
at a news conference before the blast us and soviet diplomats 
who carved out the historic agreement expressed differing opinions 
on the cessation of nuclear testing 
igor palenykh head of the soviet delegation to the nuclear 
testing talks in geneva said his countrys goal is a total ban on 
testing 
i would like to emphasize that endeavor palenykh said 
through an interpreter as far as the soviet union is concerned 
we are prepared at any time to cease nuclear testing along with the 
united states 
he referred to the soviets 18month unilateral test moratorium 
that ended last year with the resumption of soviet testing 
unfortunately this action of ours has not been appropriately 
reciprocated this doesnt mean were not willing to resolve this 
problem step by step palenykh said 
us ambassador c paul robinson palenykhs counterpart at the 
nuclear test talks said the united states believes there is a 
need for nuclear testing as long as there is a need for nuclear 
weapons for national defense 
he said it remains to be seen how we will accomodate the 
differing views on the need for nuclear testing 
robinson said todays test indicates the two countries are 
still making progress for measures for a safer world 
the test was designed to measure the ability of each country to 
monitor the size of the others nuclear tests a requisite in 
preventing cheating on treaties signed in 1974 and 1976 limiting 
the size of nuclear tests to 150 kilotons 
both sides have accused each other of exceeding the limits 
president reagan first suggested such a verification test during 
a united nations speech four years ago 
the test code named kearsarge would be the ninth at the site 
this year and the 684th announced blast at the nevada site since 
testing began here in 1951 
fortyfive soviet nuclear scientists engineers and diplomats 
were on hand to witness todays blast a like number of american 
scientists will witness a test at the soviet site at semipalatinsk 
next month 
some of the soviet scientists were in the nearby town of mercury 
when six of the previous us tests were conducted this year but 
todays test was the first one in which they were present 
one possible hitch was eliminated monday when a patrolling 
department of energy helicopter picked up two antinuclear 
protesters in a remote desert canyon a spokesman for the 
antinuclear american peace test said the two had planned to hike 
to pahute mesa to delay todays test 
energy department spokeswoman barbara yoerg said the two never 
made it to the test site boundaries they were released on a 
highway off the test site without being charged 
the us and soviet scientists planned to monitor the blast via 
highlysophisticated equipment housed in unmanned trailers several 
hundred yards from ground zero 
the 25 million test was designed to measure the size of a blast 
and was not directly related to a possible test ban although 
scientists and diplomats say the experiment was a critical first 
step down that long road 
systems to measure the size of an explosion are considered a key 
in ratifying the 1974 threshold test ban treaty and the 1976 
peaceful nuclear explosions treaty the pacts limit nuclear tests 
to 150 kilotons and both sides have accused the other of exceeding 
those limits 
c paul robinson the us arms negotiator who helped forge the 
test agreement called the test unprecedented the result of a 
breakthrough in negotiations between the superpowers the tests 
were agreed to by reagan and soviet general secretary mikhail 
gorbachev at the washington summit last december 
</TEXT>
