<TEXT>
with the death wednesday of ambassador arnold 
l raphel the state department has lost one of its most seasoned 
experts in the tumultuous southwest asian region 
raphel the us ambassador to pakistan had spent most of his 
22year diplomatic career on the politics of that region before his 
death in a plane crash that also claimed the life of pakistani 
president mohammed zia ulhaq and 35 others 
he was appointed ambassador to pakistan in january 1987 having 
served an earlier tour of duty there as political counselor from 
197578 
during the iran hostage crisis of 197981 raphel was deeply 
involved in efforts to secure the captives release working as a 
special assistant to thensecretary of state cyrus r vance and 
vances successor edmund s muskie 
present and former colleagues of raphel 45 mourned his death 
vice president george bush told a news conference in new orleans 
that raphel was an outstanding ambassador and said he knew him 
well 
also in new orleans secretary of state george shultz called for 
a moment of silence at a luncheon he was attending he called 
raphel a man of immense ability whod been doing a superb job 
at the state department spokeswoman phyllis oakley said we 
mourn the loss of ambassador raphel the united states has lost one 
of its best diplomats 
vance said in a statement issued from his office in new york 
that he was heartsick over raphels death 
he was a superb foreign service officer and a wonderful 
friend vance said our country and all of us who were 
privileged to know him have suffered a great loss 
with a mustache thick eyeglasses and a serious demeanor raphel 
had a professorial appearance his dress usually was more casual 
than that of his state department colleagues 
few countries are considered more important to the united states 
than pakistan reagans decision to send raphel there as ambassador 
was one reflection of the high esteem in which he was held 
pakistan was a conduit for us aid to rebels in neighboring 
afghanistan and zia was a favorite among conservatives here for 
his willingness to cooperate with american policy 
some conservatives including sen gordon humphrey rnh had 
deep reservations about the choice of raphel to be ambassador to 
pakistan expressing concern about his commitment to afghan rebels 
humphrey worked against raphels senate confirmation last year 
in pakistan raphel oversaw a us aid program totaling more 
than 600 million the third largest behind israel and egypt the 
administration felt pakistan was entitled to generous treatment 
despite concerns it was secretly developing a nuclear capability 
and was a source of heroin trafficking to the united states 
before his appointment by president reagan as ambassador to 
pakistan in 1987 raphel held senior positions in the 
politicalmilitary affairs bureau and the middle east bureau of the 
state department 
he was involved in southwest asian affairs for more than 20 
years beginning with his assignment to isfahan iran as a 24year 
old state department recruit in 1967 two years later he was 
assigned to tehran 
raphel was born on march 16 1943 in troy ny and received 
his bachelor of arts degree from hamilton college in 1964 before 
joining the foreign service he earned a masters degree from 
syracuse university 
raphel was recently married to nancy ely a state department 
official he had a daughter by a previous marriage 
in ventnor nj wednesday raphels family recalled that he 
wanted to be in the foreign service since he was a youngster 
as a boy raphel read books about foreign countries exploring 
ways he could someday visit the exotic locations said his brother 
murray raphel an atlantic city businessman and civic leader 
from the time he was 10 years old arnold wanted to be in the 
state department raphel said when he was 12 he wrote a 
letter to the secretary of state and asked how he could become a 
foreign service officer 
the secretary of state wrote back and said he should go to 
college even suggesting some good schools 
the family was concerned about the appointment because of the 
volatile political climate in the middle east raphel said 
but arnie never felt worried he said he felt he was 
performing a service for his country he honestly felt he could do 
the job better than anyone else 
