authorities arrested 87 people 
wednesday in a sweep through southern west virginia kentucky and 
ohio following an 18month investigation into the theft of 16 
million worth of cars trucks and heavy equipment 
terry ethridge assistant agent in charge of the pittsburgh 
division of the fbi said the investigation netted more than 120 
motor vehicles and heavy equipment some of which was displayed at 
a news conference at the huntington civic center 
officers also recovered five pounds of cocaine and numerous 
automatic weapons ethridge said 
the undercover operation was devised in early 1987 when law 
enforcement officials became aware that wed had a significant 
theft of property problem in this area he said undercover 
police simply put out the word that they were in the market to buy 
stolen auto parts vehicles and equipment 
it was relatively easy said michael carey us attorney 
for the southern district of west virginia 
the various thefts were not necessarily related to one another 
the two justice department officials said 
it would be wrong to assume all these people were part of one 
ring carey said 
the use of the term ring is misleading ethridge added 
if youre in the plumbing business you know other plumbers 
even if youre not in business with them 
carey called the operation the largest case in the district 
and one of the largest in the nation 
the thefts had a significant economic impact in the area 
especially when it came to heavy equipment tractortrailer rigs 
and coal trucks many of which are owned by independent 
owneroperators he said 
imagine if youre a coal truck driver waking up one morning 
and finding your truck gone the prosecutor said that puts you 
out of business for a long time 
we hope this will get the message out to all persons that 
the next time you sell a stolen car or truck you might be selling 
to a police officer he added 
on monday federal grand juries sitting in charleston and 
huntington returned a total of 27 indictments charging 69 
individuals with 141 counts of violating federal statutes 
including charges of conspiracy possession and transportation of 
stolen motor vehicles in interstate commerce altering 
identification numbers of vehicles and insurance fraud in 
addition other individuals charged in the case in federal and 
state court bring the total number charged to 87 officials said 
the arrests went smoothly ethridge said and federal agents and 
state and local police brought defendants to the federal 
courthouses in huntington and charleston 
more charges and arrests may result as agents follow up all 
the leads generated by the undercover operation he said 
