<TEXT>
hundreds of peruvians have been killed and 
thousands have been tortured or disappeared in provinces where the 
military has extraordinary power under a state of emergency 
amnesty international said thursday 
a report by the worldwide human rights organization said the 
disappearances and killings by the armed forces increased in the 
past two years after declining significantly following president 
alan garcias inauguration in july 1985 
londonbased amnesty said in a statement that it has received 
numerous new accounts of abuses since its report was prepared in 
may which appear to indicate a deterioration in the human rights 
situation 
amnesty called on peru to investigate impartially all the cases 
reported and bring those responsible to justice it said very few 
cases had ever been prosecuted 
the report said deaths and disappearances started in 1983 after 
the government introduced special measures to combat the 
maoistinspired shining path guerrilla group which is trying to 
overthrow perus elected government 
army officers were given military and political control over 
designated emergency zones which amnesty said enables the armed 
forces to sidestep human rights safeguards in peruvian law 
the greatest toll of victims has been reported from a remote 
mountainous area in ayacucho department which was the first 
emergency zone established the report said 
human rights groups in peru estimate 3200 people have 
disappeared since 1982 in ayacucho alone it said 
amnesty said other zones placed under military command since 
garcia came to power have been the scene of hundreds of other 
disappearances and killings 
today over 30 of perus more than 170 provinces are within 
emergency zones disappearances and extrajudicial executions 
continue to be reported on an almost daily basis in these areas 
the report said 
it said most victims were peasants students teachers 
community leaders trade union leaders lawyers and human rights 
workers in emergency zones where guerrilla groups have been most 
active 
amnesty also condemned killings and tortures by the shining path 
and other leftwing guerrillas 
in 1987 amnesty said it received reports of 201 disappearances 
175 of which remain unresolved almost half were in the ayacucho 
emergency zone 
amnesty said reports persist of civilians being seized and 
killed outright by troops or being found dead after being detained 
and of the killing of combatants after surrender 
among 36 possible militarylinked killings it cited in 1988 it 
said 29 were villagers in cayara in ayacucho department who died 
during an armed forces counterinsurgency operation may 14 
witnesses said five victims were taken by the military to the 
local church where they were beaten and hacked to death others 
were killed as they returned home from tending crops the report 
said 
reports of widespread torture included electric shocks burning 
beatings sexual abuse neardrowning and hanging by the arms for 
prolonged periods the report said 
