<TEXT>
the drought may be hindering a rally in 
the value of upper midwestern farmland but most agricultural 
bankers expect stable land prices going into the fall according to 
a new survey 
the survey of 500 bankers in five states indicates the value of 
farmland in the region rose only 1 percent during the second 
quarter of 1988 peter heffernan an analyst with the federal 
reserve bank of chicago said in a recent interview 
nevertheless the rising prices represented the sixth 
consecutive quarter of increases following a slump in land values 
over the first half of this decade 
regional land values were hardest hit by the drought in 
michigan where prices dropped nearly 2 percent and in wisconsin 
where prices fell 1 percent the survey indicated 
illinois land values rose 14 percent during the apriljune 
quarter iowa land values rose 32 percent and indiana land values 
remained stable 
undoubtedly the problems and uncertainties surrounding the 
effects of the drought had a significant bearing on their 
responses said heffernan the bankers expectations regarding 
the third quarter trend in farmland values is less optimistic than 
in earlier surveys 
heffernan said 31 percent of the bankers expected land prices to 
decline during the third quarter of 1988 while 60 percent 
predicted stable land values during july august and september 
nine percent expect prices to rise this quarter he said 
intense heat and one of the worst droughts of the century have 
combined to severely damage key us farm crops such as corn and 
soybeans the fall harvest of those commodities is expected to be 
sharply reduced 
but university of illinois land economist john scott said his 
survey of more than 400 farm appraisers in illinois iowa indiana 
and ohio suggests the drought will have only a minor impact on land 
prices 
the consensus that emerged from the responses was that if the 
drought has any impact at all it will only last one year and might 
represent a short decline in land values said scott 
he said the appraisers expect any crop losses in 1988 to be 
offset by a good production year in 1989 and then land prices 
will move to higher levels in coming years 
scott also said higher commodity prices resulting from the small 
harvest and the reduction of the grain surplus will help the land 
market rally 
while those factors might tempt farmers to invest in more land 
to expand their operations scott urged caution 
only when a farmer is financially capable and can pencil out 
through his revenue projections the ability to pay for the land 
should he consider buying it said scott 
he said the next rally in land prices would be different from 
the one in the 1970s which was fueled by inflation he said some 
farmers thought inflation would pay for the land and they spent 
more for it than they ever could recover from farm earnings 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

