<TEXT>
over the next decade exports by young 
hightechnology companies could help reduce the national trade 
deficit according to economists who unveiled a new survey of such 
firms 
as we evolve into a technologydriven type manufacturer 
these companies do start exporting shortly after they are 
born james m howell bank of bostons chief economist said 
tuesday in this environment they can be substantial 
contributors to exports 
the banks survey of nearly 400 firms nationwide indicated many 
hightech firms are exporting soon after formation and not 
experiencing a significant competitive disadvantage 
hightech companies which are concentrated on the two coasts 
will play a significant role in job growth in the next five years 
and could make a fairly substantial contribution to reducing 
the foreign trade deficit by the mid1990s howell said 
the commerce department said tuesday that the us trade deficit 
for june increased to 125 billion a 285 percent increase over 
mays 98 billion imbalance and the worst monthly figure since 
february 
the bank survey was mailed earlier this year to 6539 companies 
in the fields of biotechnology advanced materials photonic and 
optics automation and test and measurement 
hightech exporters formed during the 1980s with annual sales of 
under 10 million have had about the same or in some cases faster 
sales and employment growth rates as nonexporting firms the 
survey indicated 
most of the jobs in the country get created by young hightech 
companies growing up howell said theres a difference between 
a digital equipment corp growing up from the 50s to the 80s 
and a corner drug store not growing at all 
the survey indicated sales increased by 50 percent and 
employment by 23 percent among young export firms in the most 
recent fiscal year compared to 44 percent and 26 percent 
respectively among nonexporting firms 
technology concentrations in the form of manufacturing firms and 
research facilities are a major source of new development because 
they serve as the spawning ground for entrepreneurs and as a 
significant source of new products and processes the survey said 
the young exporters perceive europe and japan as their primary 
sources of comptition but in only one of the five fields did a 
majority of companies think that competition is unfair sixtyseven 
percent of test and measurement companies thought competition was 
too stiff compared to 22 percent in biotechnology and 18 percent 
in photonic and optics 
gaining market share in a rapidly expanding global market is 
viewed as being far more important than the fairness of the 
marketplace the survey said 
this finding strikes us as significant and suggests that the 
current preoccupation with protectionism misses the mark it 
said from a policy perspective it will be more productive to 
focus on the issue of creating a hospitable environment for 
business starts 
</TEXT>
