<TEXT>
demand for petroleum products declined in july 
along with a falloff in domestic crude oil production but imports 
reached their highest level in about a year the american petroleum 
institute reported wednesday 
according to the institutes monthly statistical report 
deliveries of petroleum products a key measure of demand fell 23 
percent to an average 167 million barrels a day when compared with 
yearago figures 
despite continued growth in both the economy and in highway 
travel julys limp gasoline deliveries continued the nogrowth 
patternof the second quarter the washingtonbased institute said 
but api noted that deliveries strengthened consistently as the 
month progressed indicating fairly healthy deliveries by 
monthend 
domestic crude oil production fell 12 percent from the yearago 
period to an average 82 million barrels a day 
despite the drop in crude production the institute noted that 
the production of natural gas liquids averaged 16 million barrels 
a day natural gas liquids account for about 10 percent of the 
nations petroleum supplies 
the institute noted that the average 73 million barrels a day 
in imported petroleum goods during july came close to last julys 
recentyear record the united states is dependent upon imports 
for nearly 44 percent of its oil needs 
in other highlights the institute reported 
total inventories were up 13 percent from june and were 63 
percent higher than in the yearago period 
the nations refineries continued to operate at high levels 
reaching 869 percent of capacity in july 
for the first seven months of the year imports were up a hefty 
113 percent while demand was up 17 percent over the 1987 period 
crude production was down during the period 
